{
  "texts": [
    "Kim and Jeon [27] exploited the traditional Kalman filter for multiple object tracking of radar and visible images.",
    "Megherbi et al. [28] proposed a tracking method by combining vision and audio information using belief theory.",
    "In this study, tracking of RGB-D and RGB-T data, using a portable and affordable binocular camera, is the focus.",
    "As shown in Fig. 1, thermal images capture the target temperature and are not sensitive to lighting conditions, rain, or fog, which can make the tracker work day and night.",
    "Depth data provide relative distance between targets and camera and can easily detect target occlusion and capture target boundaries."
  ]
}